The rand weakened against the dollar early on Wednesday as US-China trade tensions sparked market fears that the standoff between the world’s two largest economies could spiral into a trade war which could crush global growth. At 06:31 GMT, the rand traded at 11.86 per dollar, 0.3% weaker than its overnight close. US President Donald Trump administration announced 25% tariffs on $50 billion of annual imports from China, covering around 1,300 industrial technology, transport and medical products. China’s commerce ministry immediately warned it was preparing countermeasures of equal intensity. “Global trade tensions continue to weigh on risk appetite, and until common ground is found safe-haven demand would remain as the best form of defence,” Nedbank analysts wrote in a note. In fixed income, the yield for the benchmark government bond was up 1.5 basis points to 8.03%.